@lemonltea tf.stop_gradient() is an operation that acts as the identity function in the forward direction, but stops the accumulated gradient from flowing through that operator in the backward direction. It does not prevent backpropagation altogether, but instead prevents an individual tensor from contributing to the gradients that are computed for an expression. The documentation for the [operation](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/stop_gradient) has more details about the operation, and when to use it.

In short, tf.stop_gradient provides a way to not compute gradient with respect to some variables during back-propagation.

Please check this SO [link](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33727935/how-to-use-stop-gradient-in-tensorflow) where they have explained in a very detailed manner. Thanks!

